You can solve this problem in Java without loops/recursion by using logarithms. Here's a one-liner solution:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return 1 < n && 1162261467 % n == 0 ? (Math.log(n) / Math.log(3) % 1 == 0) : (n == 1);
    }
}
// Alternatively, a more concise version:
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) { return n > 0 && Math.pow(3, (int)Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)) == n; }
```

Explanation: 

The mathematical idea is to check if the base 3 logarithm of the number is an integer. If it is, then `n` is a power of 3.

In the first solution, I added a check for `n > 1` (and a special case for `n == 1`) because 0 and negative numbers are not powers of 3. The magic number `1162261467` is actually 3^19, the largest power of 3 that fits in an integer in Java.

In the second solution, I combined the conditions into a single line. Java performs integer division first when both operands are integers, so `(int)Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)` will truncate the result to an integer, effectively checking if the log is an integer. If it is a power of 3, the pow function will return the original number.

